## Migration: Thread.Abort → Cooperative Cancellation (.NET 8)

### Why This Breaks

In .NET 6+, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — it simply doesn't work. `ThreadAbortException` is never raised, and `Thread.ResetAbort()` is obsolete (`SYSLIB0006`).

### Pattern Classification

| Original Code | Pattern | Replacement |
|---|---|---|
| `while (_running)` loop | Cancellable work loop | `CancellationToken` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Control flow cleanup | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Continue after abort | Check `IsCancellationRequested` |
| `_workerThread.Abort()` | Force stop | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token to unblock waits
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Clean up partial work (migrated from ThreadAbortException handler)
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed — just continue to let the loop exit naturally
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Wait with a timeout instead of Thread.Sleep + Abort
        _workerThread?.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

### Key Changes Explained

1. **`_running` → `CancellationToken`** — The volatile bool is replaced by a token that can also interrupt blocking calls.

2. **`GetNextItem()` must accept a token** — If it blocks (e.g., `BlockingCollection.Take`), pass the token so it throws `OperationCanceledException` when cancelled. Without this, cancellation stalls until the blocking call returns naturally.

3. **`Thread.Sleep(2000)` + `Abort()` → `Join(timeout)`** — `Join` blocks until the thread exits or the timeout elapses. No force-kill needed because the thread cooperates.

4. **`IDisposable`** — `CancellationTokenSource` leaks timers/callbacks if not disposed.

### Critical Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Impact |
|---|---|
| Not passing token to `GetNextItem` | Thread hangs forever on blocked call; `Stop()` never completes |
| Catching `OperationCanceledException` without `when` filter | Swallows unrelated cancellations from inner operations |
| Forgetting to dispose `CancellationTokenSource` | Timer/callback memory leaks |
| Expecting instant cancellation | Only works at checkpoints — add `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` inside `ProcessItem` if it's long-running |
| Using a new `volatile bool` alongside the token | Redundant and error-prone; use only the token |

### If `GetNextItem` Cannot Be Modified

If it's a blocking call you don't control (e.g., third-party library), replace `Thread.Sleep`-based waiting with:

```csharp
// Wrap uncooperative blocking in a Task and use WaitAsync
var workTask = Task.Run(() => GetNextItem());
var item = await workTask.WaitAsync(token); // .NET 6+ API
```

Or as a last resort, move the work to a child `Process` and use `Process.Kill()` — the only safe way to forcibly terminate uncooperative code in modern .NET.
